'''Quadratic voting''' (sometimes abbreviated QV) is a collective [[decision-making]] procedure, where participants cast their ''preference'' and ''intensity of preference'' for each decision (as opposed to a simple ''for'' or ''against'' decision).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lalley|first=Steven|last2=Weyl|first2=E. Glen|date=2017-12-24|title=Quadratic Voting: How Mechanism Design Can Radicalize Democracy|url=https://papers.ssrn.com/abstract=2003531|language=en|location=Rochester, NY|doi=10.2139/ssrn.2003531}}</ref>
According to its authors [https://galton.uchicago.edu/~lalley/ Steven P. Lalley] and [http://glenweyl.com/ E. Glen Weyl], '''Quadratic voting''' is claimed to achieve the greatest possible good for the greatest number of group members<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collectivedecisionengines.com/quadratic-voting.html|title=Quadratic Voting|website=collectivedecisionengines.com|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref> although other proponents of Quadratic Voting admit that is at best an approximation<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1030268293|title=Radical Markets: uprooting capitalism and democracy for a just society|last=Posner|first=Eric|authorlink=Eric Posner|last2=Weyl|first2=E. Glen|isbn=9780691177502|location=Princeton|oclc=1030268293|year=2018}}</ref>. It addresses issues of [[voting paradox]] and [[Majority rule|majority-rule]].
Based on market principles, each voter is endowed with a [[budget]] of “voice credits” that they may spend influencing the outcome of a range of decisions. If a participant has a strong preference for or against a particular decision, additional votes can be allocated. A vote [[pricing]] rule determines the cost of additional votes, whereby each vote increasingly becomes more expensive.
The quadratic nature of the voting means that a voter can use his or her votes more efficiently spread across many issues. For example a voter with a budget of 16 vote credits can apply 1 vote credit to each of 16 issues. But if they feel strongly about a single issue and apply 4 votes at the cost of 16 credits to a single issue. This will use their entire budget. This also means there is a large incentive to buy and sell votes, although using a strictly secret ballot gives some protection against vote buying as the purchase cannot be verified. {| class="wikitable" |+Vote Pricing Example !Number of votes !“Voice Credit” cost |- |1 |1 |- |2 |4 |- |3 |9 |- |4 |16 |- |5 |25 |}
